  "summary": "Charles and his father discuss Sophia's refusal to provide information, noting her preference that he view the situation from an outsider's perspective. Inspector Taverner arrives to discuss the ongoing investigation into the Leonidis family. Charles's father explains that Aristide Leonidis, a Greek immigrant, built a catering empire by exploiting legal loopholes. Aristide lived in Swinley with his family; of his eight children, only two survived: Roger, who is childless, and Philip, who lives at Mounted Gables with his wife, his three children—Eustace, Josephine, and Sophia—and his sister-in-law, Miss Harvillan.\n\nTaverner confirms that Aristide was murdered by poisoning, likely with aconitine, a component found in his own eyedrops. The father reveals that ten years ago, the seventy-five-year-old Aristide remarried a twenty-four-year-old woman from a teahouse. Taverner notes that this second wife has a young lover who serves as the tutor to Leonidis' grandsons. The investigation suggests the wife may have injected Aristide with a poisoned bottle instead of his required insulin. However, Taverner remains suspicious of this theory because the wife did not replace the poisoned bottle with a legitimate one, an act that would have made the crime much harder to detect. The presence of both full and empty insulin bottles in the house makes the trace of the specific poisoned bottle a key piece of evidence.",
